evidence:
packages/voice-tts-gemini/src/index.ts is non-streaming by construction. tts.text only accumulates into a Map, never synthesizes:
  bus.on("tts.text", (pkt) => { const current = this.textByContextId.get(textPkt.contextId) ?? ""; this.textByContextId.set(textPkt.contextId, current + textPkt.text); });
Synthesis fires once, on tts.done, with the full accumulated text:
  bus.on("tts.done", async (pkt) => { const buffered = this.textByContextId.get(donePkt.contextId) ?? ""; ... const text = donePkt.text || buffered; ... await this.synthesize(text, donePkt.contextId); });
synthesizeOnce makes a single blocking client.models.generateContent({ responseModalities: ['AUDIO'] }) call wrapped in withTimeout, then loops over response.candidates[0].content.parts pushing tts.audio AFTER the full response resolves. So no audio leaves until the entire synthesis completes -> TTFA == full synthesis latency. The header comment itself states this: 'Non-streaming (chunked) -- sends full text, receives complete audio' and 'Gemini TTS returns chunked audio for complete text, not true token-by-token low-latency streaming.'
Contrast: voice-tts-deepgram/src/index.ts synthesizes incrementally per delta -- bus.on("tts.text", async (pkt) => { await this.speak(textPkt.text, textPkt.contextId); }) sends each sentence to a held-open WebSocket as the LLM produces it, so first audio returns mid-turn. Cartesia is likewise WebSocket-streaming (wss://api.cartesia.ai/tts/websocket). Gemini is the only TTS plugin that defers all synthesis to tts.done.
